---
import ServiceLayout from '../../layouts/ServiceLayout.astro';

const title = "Warehouse Line Striping Springfield MO | Industrial Floor Markings";
const description = "Warehouse floor markings, forklift lanes, and safety striping in Springfield MO. We connect you with certified contractors for high-traffic industrial and distribution center applications.";
const h1 = "Warehouse Line Striping in Springfield, Missouri";
---

<ServiceLayout {title} {description} {h1}>
  <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-concrete leading-relaxed">
    <p class="text-xl">We connect warehouse operators and facility managers with certified contractors who specialize in warehouse floor markings, forklift lanes, pedestrian walkways, and industrial safety striping.</p>
    
    <p>High-traffic industrial environments require durable markings that improve safety and operational efficiency. Standard parking lot paint often fails under constant forklift traffic.</p>

    <h2>Warehouse Striping Services</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Forklift lanes and pedestrian walkways</li>
      <li>Loading dock approach markings</li>
      <li>Storage zone and racking aisle identification</li>
      <li>Safety and hazard zone striping</li>
      <li>High-durability paint and thermoplastic options</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Typical Cost Ranges</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Small warehouse (under 10,000 sq ft):</strong> $2,800 – $6,500</li>
      <li><strong>Medium warehouse (10,000–30,000 sq ft):</strong> $5,500 – $12,000</li>
      <li><strong>Large distribution center:</strong> $10,000 – $25,000+</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    
    <h3>What materials hold up best in warehouses?</h3>
    <p>Epoxy-based and thermoplastic markings generally perform best in high-traffic industrial environments compared to standard traffic paint.</p>

    <h3>Can work be done without shutting down operations?</h3>
    <p>Yes. Most warehouse striping is completed in phases during off-shift hours or weekends.</p>
  </div>
</ServiceLayout>